For patients with acute hypernatremia (<48 h), rapid lowering of serum sodium by 1 mmol/h by the administration of hypotonic fluids does not increase the risk of cerebral edema, whereas those with hypernatremia of unknown or longer duration a slower pace of correction, aiming for around 10 mmol/L/day is important to prevent cerebral edema. As the risk of cerebral edema also depends upon the volume infused, then smaller volumes of more hypotonic fluids are advantageous [55].\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
